field.value:
Support classes "Data Import Source" and "Data Import Report"

 

There is a special class Data Import Source, which is used for importing data from spreadsheet in the system.

It is possible in this special class to restrict the permission on the users who would be able to import data, to define special state machine and to provide a detailed help about the format and process of import.

  • The object of type Data Import Source, is uploadable and searchable.
    • The Data Import Source has the following states as a minimum: For import, Successful import, Partial import. Other states could be defined per client if for example the import file should go in review and approval process.

Example:

  • Objects of type Data Import Source are uploadable (1-2-3-4-5-6-7).

  • There is a class Data Import Report in which the user receives information for the data validation.
    • The Data Import Report that is not creatable/ uploadable, but is searchable.

Example:

  • Objects of type Data Import Source are searchable (1, 3).
  • Objects of type Data Import Report are searchable (2, 4).

Import files from spreadsheet

Validate data file and generate text report before the import

The file format and the data in the import file are validated before the import, and the user receives a report which displays the result of the validation.

Validation Rules:

  1. Validation for file format - Check if the file selected for import is in the proper mime type. If not then in the report file there is a message: "Wrong file format."
  2. Validation for existing object type - Check for each entity in the import file if in the system exist that type. If not then for this row is written: "There is no object of that type in the system."
  3. Validation for creatable object type - Check for each object type in the file if it is creatable or uploadable. If the object type is only uploadable then in the report is written: "Object of that type is not allowed to be created."
  4. Validation for user create permissions - Check if the user has create permissions for the respective object type. If not then display a message: "The current user doesn't have permissions to create object of that type."
  5. Validation for property validity - Check if the property of that type is valid for the respective object type (in a row for one object type could be entered property which is valid for other object type, because the user might enter by mistake this data in the wrong field). If the property is not valid then message is displayed: "Property <property ID> is not valid for that object type."
  6. Validation for property value- Check each property for type (string, date, number, etc.), size (10, 1000 symbols, etc.), code-list values, condition, etc. If a property is wrong and one or more of the data validations do not pass, then message is displayed to the user with the result of the validation: "property ID (URI): Error message"
  7. Validation for mandatory property - Check if there is a value for all mandatory properties for that object type. If a mandatory property is missing then in the report file is written: "property ID (URI): The property is mandatory."
  • The user uploads an .xls file as Data Import Source in a project (1-2-3-4-5-6-7-8-9).
  • The user opens the uploaded file.
  • There is action Import file for Data Import Source object and the user selects it (1-2-3)

 

Select context for data import

 

  • The system opens a screen with title "Select context" (1). In the screen is displayed the default context (2) for data import (the default context is the context in which the Date Import Source file is uploaded) in which the data from the import file will be created.
    • The user could change the default context (2) in case he/ she wants the imported records to be created in different context than the default.
  • In the "Select context" screen there is action "Validate file" (3). The user selects it.
  • If there are entities in the file to be updated, and the selected context for data import is different than the context in which the entity exists, then during the import the context of the entity is updated together with the rest of the properties for the entity in the file (it is like move action).
  • The validation of the file format and the data in the file starts. A message is displayed that validation is in process (1).
  • After the validation, a text report is generated with the result from the file and data validation. Only error messages are provided in the report.
  • A Confirmation pop-up (2) is displayed with options Import file(4) and Cancel(5).
    • A link to the report file is displayed (3), so that the user could open it.
      • The report file is named with FileImportValidation_timestamp.txt.
      • The report file is saved in the context of the Data Import File.
      • The user clicks on the link to the report (3).

In case of a wrong validation for the file format, then Data validation on all entities in the file is not performed and the user cannot select action Import file, but only Cancel.

The report file is opened in a new tab, so that the user could continue with the real import from the screen.

 

 

Import data from spreadsheet

The system automatically creates objects in the system, by importing data from spreadsheet files.

  • The user selects from the Confirmation pop-up (1) the option "Import File". 
  • When the user selects "Import file" after the performed validation, then the system starts to import the data from the file row by row (only for the rows which are valid).
    • If all data in a row have passed the validation, then an object of the respective type is created with the properties described in the spreadsheet and system data (creator, date created, ID, etc) based on who and when performed the action Import file.
  • The user is informed of the running process and the successful operation.
  • The imported files from the Data Import Source are visible as children of the project .
  • Each new object is created by default in the same context in which exists the Data import source file.
  • For each entity created during the import a flag on the entity is automatically set with value "Spreadsheet imported" .
  • The action Import file is logged in the Audit log and the creation of each of the objects is also logged as separate Create action.

Generate result file after the import

 

After the import is completed (1), the user is able to see in the Data Import Source file which records were imported and which did not pass the validations (2), so that he/ she can review the errors and fix them.

  • When the import procedure starts  then 2 new columns are added in the file: ID (URI) (3) and Import status (4). If the columns already exist then new columns are not created.
  • For each row from the spreadsheet file that is successfully imported in the ID (URI) column is written the unique identifier of the newly created object (5), in Import status column is written the value "Successfully imported" (6).
  • For each row from the spreadsheet file that is not successfully imported in the Import status column is written value "Not imported".
  • The spreadsheet file with import result is saved as new version of the original file (the version number is incremented) and the system properties modified by, modified on are updated also.
  • If all records are imported with status Successfully imported, then the status of the document changes to Successful Import (6).
  • If there are successfully imported records but one or more records not imported, then the status of the document changes to Partial import.
  • Note: If the file is downloaded - the two new columns are visible at the end.

Import the same file twice and more

 

In case of errors in the performed validation process the user could fix the problems in the excel file and/or update some of the successfully imported records, and then is able to import it again.

Example:

  • The import is performed partially  - two files are imported successfully and one file is not imported .
  • The errors are visible in the Data Import Report .
  • The errors should be fixed in the downloaded excel file (according the validation errors in the Data Import Report).
  • The user fixes the error/s (entering data in the mandatory field Description) in the downloaded excel file.
  • The user selects the action Upload New Version for the Data Import Source file.
  • The new version is uploaded (1). The status of the Data Import Source file changes to "For import" .
  • The user performs again the action "Import file".
  • A new  Data Import Report file is generated .
  • When action Import file is selected on file which has already been imported then the file and data validation starts.
    • If in the excel file there is row with value in ID column, containing the ID of an existing object in the system, and all of the validations pass for this row, then existing object is updated with the all the values in the file, and system data are updated also (modified by, modified on) based on who and when made the new import, and a new version is created.
    • If during the import an object with ID the same as the value in the ID column is not found, then this object is created with new automatically generated ID, which is returned back in the ID column.
  • All rows in the excel file for which there is no value in the ID column are validated and imported if all validations pass, or not imported if there are some errors.
  • The status of the object of type Data Import Source file is updated respectively to Successful import, Partial import.
  • For all successfully imported new items and updated items the status is "Successfully imported" and the ID of the created/ updated item is filled in the ID column.
  • For all items that do not pass the validations (both new and existing) in the Import status are listed the validation errors. After the new import is completed a new result excel file is generated and uploaded with updated columns ID and Import status . In the example - a new object is created with new automatically generated ID .
  • In the audit log Edit action is logged for the updated items.

Multi-sheet import

 

The user is able to import spreadsheet file with more that one sheets in it.

  • The records from all sheets are imported.
  • All sheets are imported one by one, starting from the first (the most left one).
  • For all validation errors in the result validation file there is information for the sheet name before the row number.

Search for an object and create object properties in the import file

 

If there is a column in the excel file that contains object property (contains relationship to other object) then the system searches for the existing object and the respective relationship is created between the imported object and the related object.

Rules:

  • For each object property in the excel file is provided information about the object type, and for one or more properties of that object type that are entered in the excel file in the respective column
  • When the validation on excel file is done, then for each value in the respective column a search is performed for object type with properties that equal the value.
    • If an object with the respective property/ properties is not found in the system then a message is displayed in the validation file for that property "Object of that type and this property could not be found in the system.".
    • If more than one objects are found with the respective property/ properties then a message is displayed in the validation file for that property "More than one objects are found with those criteria.".
    • If an object with the respective property/ properties is found then a relationship of the respective type is created between the found object and newly created one.

Search for an object in a context and create object properties in the import file

 

If there is a column in the excel file that contains object property (contains relationship to other object) then the system to search for existing object in a context and the respective relationship is created between the imported object and the related object.

Rules:

  • For an object property in the excel file could be provided in addition information if the search for the object type the properties of that object type to be executed in a context. The context is the same, selected during the import for the creation of the objects.
  • When the validation on excel file is done, then for each value in the respective column a search is performed for object type with properties that equal the value in the cell, but only in the selected for import context.
    • If an object with the respective property/ properties is not found in the context then a message is displayed in the validation file for that property "Object of that type and this property could not be found in the system.".
    • If an object with the respective property/ properties is found then a relationship of the respective type is created between the found object and newly created one.

Search for an object based on additional search criteria

 

The user is able to define additional search criteria, based on which to search for object properties in the spreadsheet.

Rules:

  • For each object property in the excel file could be provided additional search criteria (for example date created, status, etc.), which will help for better identification of the object entered in the excel file in the respective column.
  • During the import only objects that cover the search criteria are searched and linked with newly created object.
  • In the additional search criteria could be provided only data properties for the linked objects (not object properties).
    • Only "equal" for the respective data properties is performed.
